element_texts.text:
San Jose. March 21st, 1899
Prof. Graham Taylor. 140 East Union St.
Chicago, Illinois.
Dear sir, 
Your kind favor of the 15 [inst?] is at hand. 
The price of the property you are considering, is high, at over $250, per front ft, still The rental value of the same, is $920. a year too much, but if local reasons advise the purchase of it, you likely can not do much better. 
I believe I answered your former letter, but don't know now, just what I wrote you. But paying no regard to what I then said, I feel a renewed mistrust in your present
enterprise. If yourself and trustees are sure there will be no failure in carrying it through, I am ready to send my check for $500, towards payment of first $2000, and also will pay you $1000 more when required, at the end of the year. Provided the balance, of the purchase money,

element_texts.text:
is subscribed, before making my last payment. 
From all I can gather from your letter, I am confident that you are on the way to success, in this grand work for the Lord, and humanity.
My health still continues fairly good, and I trust to return to Chicago again about the 20th of July. 
With kind regards
I remain yours truly
J.M. Williams.
Dictated 
address for the present box 27. College Park, Cal.

San Jose Cal. May 22nd 1899
Professor Graham Taylor
Chicago
Dear Friend.
Your kind favor of the 13th. inst. shorthand for installment?? came duly to hand. 
I notice all you say regarding the favorable unclear which surround the noble enterprise, in which you are engaged and. Take courage therefore to respond somewhat favorably to your desires.
